{"term":"1976","caseName":"United States v. Lovasco","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1976/75-1844","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 22, 1977","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger6/oral_argument_audio/15895","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will resume arguments in United States against Lovasco.","start":0,"stop":5.301,"duration":5.3},{"text":"Mr. Gilden.","start":5.301,"stop":8.654,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":8.654,"stop":11.891,"duration":3.24},{"text":"Continuing my argument in this matter, I might say that the government at no time before in the District Court or in the Eighth Circuit ever contended that the defendant had to prove the governmental misconduct, the tactical advantage secured by the government by delaying prosecution.","start":11.891,"stop":30.61,"duration":18.72},{"text":"This is the first time that it has been raised and that is in this Court.","start":30.61,"stop":33.914,"duration":3.3},{"text":"The government conceded before the District Court that all you had to do is prove the prejudicial delay and the subsequent result in material prejudice and both elements were proved in the District Court and affirmed by the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals.","start":33.914,"stop":49.059,"duration":15.14},{"text":"It is a little bit unusual to come at this late date and say the Eighth Circuit was an error, when the same Eighth Circuit did not have these fundamentals before them at the time that the government argued its case and presented its brief to the Eighth Circuit when they said all Marion required was the delay was unreasonable and is subsequent result in material prejudice.","start":49.059,"stop":70.919,"duration":21.86}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"That you see is the defendant’s burden.","start":70.919,"stop":74.147,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"That was our burden and we proved that burden by showing the 17-month delay, by proving that the defendant had called the government from time to time on five or six occasions said, what is going on?","start":74.147,"stop":90.029,"duration":15.88},{"text":"The government conceded that he had anxiety about 1situation and then the result in prejudice in the death of, well might say that there were two witness that died.","start":90.029,"stop":101.11,"duration":11.08},{"text":"However, the District Court laid its fundamentals of material prejudice on the death of Stewart and the Eight Circuit affirmed that finding that there was material prejudice in the death of Stewart.","start":101.11,"stop":111.596,"duration":10.49},{"text":"So, there was the result in material prejudice.","start":111.596,"stop":114.311,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"That Mr. Stewart had to do only was sum of the guns not all of them.","start":114.311,"stop":118.464,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, but that was never isolated as to where -- the government never isolated or of course the government did not know which ones came from Stewart and which ones came from finding the guns in the car at the terminal of railroad mail facility.","start":118.464,"stop":134.888,"duration":16.42},{"text":"However, the Court concluded that the very essential element which is the question, did Lovasco know that the guns were stolen would be something that would be deprived of him by a trial without having this material evidence present at the any trial by the death of the witness?","start":134.888,"stop":157.133,"duration":22.25},{"text":"And the Court concluded that – what is really essential Mr. Justice Blackmun is the question that, the government did not do anything for 17 months.","start":157.133,"stop":166.511,"duration":9.38}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this is my next question, does your position depend on what the governments investigation uncovers in the interim.","start":166.511,"stop":175.34,"duration":8.83},{"text":"Suppose they had done something and it either did or did not produce something additional, your position different.","start":175.34,"stop":184.852,"duration":9.51}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"No, well our position will be different.","start":184.852,"stop":186.738,"duration":1.89},{"text":"I think that, if the government had just showed that they were trying to do something for 17 months, my position would be totally different before this Court and would have been different, I think, the proceedings refer the District Court because…","start":186.738,"stop":198.048,"duration":11.31}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But that was totally different in what respect would that had met your case?","start":198.048,"stop":201.08,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"It would meet the standards that they were continuing there investigation and they showed nothing about the continuous nature of the investigation.","start":201.08,"stop":208.344,"duration":7.26}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What you are saying is if they had proved that much?","start":208.344,"stop":210.514,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":210.514,"stop":211.333,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I say it proved that much, not withstanding the prejudice that you had proved nevertheless you would lose.","start":211.333,"stop":217.182,"duration":5.85}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that was in the framework with the statute limitations and the question of foreseeability, I do not think that the defendant can hold the government to that kind of strict proof and hold that sort of confined within a box that way.","start":217.182,"stop":232.537,"duration":15.36},{"text":"I think that is not what I asking this Court to...","start":232.537,"stop":236.162,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What if it is no question of the government, what if there is no suggestion of any deliberate delay to hurt you and no negligence, but simply a desire of the government to keep it under coverage and under covered.","start":236.162,"stop":253.355,"duration":17.19}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that was never developed.","start":253.355,"stop":254.902,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I know but let us  assume that we are true.","start":254.902,"stop":256.74,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that was case like a continuous narcotics investigation.","start":256.74,"stop":260.41,"duration":3.67},{"text":"I think that that would satisfy.","start":260.41,"stop":261.48,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that would not be a continuous investigation of you or your client, it would simply be that this agent was in place and he might be making other cases.","start":261.48,"stop":270.864,"duration":9.38}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well but they, had they presented that evidence that will satisfying the criteria.","start":270.864,"stop":275.355,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So, you think that also.","start":275.355,"stop":276.781,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"That would satisfy the criteria as well.","start":276.781,"stop":278.731,"duration":1.95},{"text":"I do not think that I -- I do not want to hamstring the government in terms of…","start":278.731,"stop":282.124,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But you would think that as long as your prejudice even in negligence, even in attention just in attention and negligence would -- that you do not even need to show that I think you just show the delay in the prejudice and then the government must explain it.","start":282.124,"stop":303.658,"duration":21.53}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"We will say something.","start":303.658,"stop":305.349,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, any reasonable explanation by the government, let see if I get this.","start":305.349,"stop":311,"duration":5.65},{"text":"The defendant concedes that it will have the burden of showing both delay and the prejudice and then the government can successfully meet that merely by showing some reasonable explanation of why the delay.","start":311,"stop":325.163,"duration":14.16}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, that is all I am asking for before this Court, I do not think that I am asking for any principles which nail the government into a justification which might meet the merits of the case or getting into substance of the issues of the case.","start":325.163,"stop":341.57,"duration":16.41},{"text":"Just showing some consideration with respect to the fact that there has been a completed investigation and now we want to get some more evidence.","start":341.57,"stop":348.956,"duration":7.39},{"text":"I might say that this Court should see the protectuality of what the government has done here.","start":348.956,"stop":355.084,"duration":6.13},{"text":"In the District Court, that the government argued and there was never any proof in the record about this.","start":355.084,"stop":360.712,"duration":5.63},{"text":"The government argued that they were trying to get evidence that the son was implicated, the defendant’s son and they want to nail him; they did not feel the defendant was guilty, but they felt the son was the guilty.","start":360.712,"stop":372.55,"duration":11.84},{"text":"Then in Eighth Circuit, they changed that argument and they said that “We want to find out, who stole the mail”.","start":372.55,"stop":379.633,"duration":7.08},{"text":"Then the government comes before this Court, in abundance both of those arguments and says to this Court, “We wanted to continue the investigation to nail the defendant, we want to get more evidence on him.”","start":379.633,"stop":391.979,"duration":12.35},{"text":"So now they have got three arguments and none of those were supported by the record in the District Court.","start":391.979,"stop":397.057,"duration":5.08},{"text":"So, I wonder with all these voluntary…","start":397.057,"stop":400.019,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose, any one or all three had been the subject of some government testimony to District Court, could you be here?","start":400.019,"stop":406.219,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"I would not be here; I would have lost my motion.","start":406.219,"stop":408.814,"duration":2.6},{"text":"I think the Court would have conceded that they gave some reason or justification for the delay and the Court found that there was no reason or justification for the delay and I would not be before this Court, well I try to probably appeal the issue, but I am sure I would have gotten very for and I do not think I would be entitled to get vary far.","start":408.814,"stop":426.513,"duration":17.7},{"text":"I think that based upon the record below, there is an absence of any reason or justification.","start":426.513,"stop":433.104,"duration":6.59}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Are not you really arguing that we are bound; we must read the statute of limitations as Congress had said, the action maybe brought within five years.","start":433.104,"stop":445.236,"duration":12.13},{"text":"But, provided that it must be brought sooner, must the government shows that it could not have been brought sooner, isn’t that really what you are arguing on the modification of the statute?","start":445.236,"stop":456.553,"duration":11.32}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I just say that this is not a question of that, I am just saying that if the government just showed that they had moved their little finger one inch that would be sufficient to show that they were doing something.","start":456.553,"stop":467.898,"duration":11.35}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Doesn’t the statute say that they can move within five years?","start":467.898,"stop":470.888,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I know but if they are interceding constitutional rights that affect the defendant by reason of the government, we say thus government stays before this Court and this is the interesting proposition.","start":470.888,"stop":482.07,"duration":11.18},{"text":"They have the Right to inertia and what troubles me so much…","start":482.07,"stop":487.931,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"What they are saying is that Congress gave them five years of inertia in statute of limitation.","start":487.931,"stop":493.336,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"They maybe entitled to inertia but I think if, that if Intervening constitutional rights come into play as here, with the death of materiel witnesses and due process comes in the picture, I do not think they have their right anymore, I think they are -- they have that responsibility to foresee that within the framework of the statute limitations, that there maybe some result in prejudice that better do something about getting this case to trial.","start":493.336,"stop":514.972,"duration":21.64}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what about a civil case, where the government is given a period to bring an action against a private individual by a statute of limitations and you can make the same showing in a civil case, does the Due Process Clause violated there?","start":514.972,"stop":532.577,"duration":17.61}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I do not think the due process -- I think you would have question of latches there, I think that is what you would have theoried there Justice Rehnquist.","start":532.577,"stop":539.104,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But if the Due Process Clause talks about deprivation of life, liberty or property, presumably a civil defendant could be deprived of property just as surly as a criminal defendant could be deprived of liberty by unwarranted government delay that was still within the limitations period.","start":539.104,"stop":555.947,"duration":16.84}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think this Court is much more concerned about fundamental constitutional rights of criminal cases than they are in civil latches.","start":555.947,"stop":561.45,"duration":5.5}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the rundamental constitutional rights you are talking about other than the right to, not be deprived of liberty without due process of law.","start":561.45,"stop":570.032,"duration":8.58}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the fundamental right is the right to a fair trial, Justice Rehnquist.","start":570.032,"stop":573.835,"duration":3.8},{"text":"If you do not have all your witnesses at trail you have not had a fair trial, and how can you go to trial when you have lost your evidence and the government…","start":573.835,"stop":581.775,"duration":7.94}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"If stood, the day after the crime, what would you have?","start":581.775,"stop":585.129,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- I might say that there was a question I was presented yesterday and I can say that certain…","start":585.129,"stop":590.667,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I still think its here.","start":590.667,"stop":592.208,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"What sir?","start":592.208,"stop":592.989,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it is still here.","start":592.989,"stop":594.433,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it may well be, but I think that certainly the Court, the District Court does not or can deal with that issue Justice Marshall or you can say that certainly that is something the government had no control over.","start":594.433,"stop":606.265,"duration":11.83},{"text":"But, the government had control over these proceedings and what is so interesting is that really bothers me so much is the government…","start":606.265,"stop":613.528,"duration":7.26}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, who determines how much evidence is available for prosecution other than the US Attorney?","start":613.528,"stop":624.749,"duration":11.22}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he is the only one…","start":624.749,"stop":625.959,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn’t that he is provocative and nobody else’s?","start":625.959,"stop":629.342,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"True, but let me say this, this is also…","start":629.342,"stop":631.533,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Weel, if he wants to little bit more, he just wants one more witness.","start":631.533,"stop":635.599,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he did not say that to the District Court, he had to…","start":635.599,"stop":637.861,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Would that been enough?","start":637.861,"stop":639.101,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"That would have been enough; he was trying to find somebody.","start":639.101,"stop":640.927,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, can’t you assume that?","start":640.927,"stop":642.616,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I can assume…","start":642.616,"stop":644.357,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"If you do not assume that he did it to deliberately, will you?","start":644.357,"stop":648.94,"duration":4.58}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me say this, I believe it was done deliberately certainly, I believe that when…","start":648.94,"stop":653.514,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what good is it to do it, to hold up prosecution deliberately?","start":653.514,"stop":657.371,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, courts have held and this Court…","start":657.371,"stop":659.791,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I was told at Law School that delay was to the benefit of the defendant because he would always rely on the prosecutor's witness dying.","start":659.791,"stop":668.073,"duration":8.28}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that is true and…","start":668.073,"stop":668.848,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Weren't you taught that in Law School.","start":668.848,"stop":669.895,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"I was taught the same thing Your Honor, but I might say too that it works for -- it is a double edge sword, it can work against defendant as well.","start":669.895,"stop":676.826,"duration":6.93},{"text":"I worked against him here and I think that certainly delay does benefit defendant, but I think that there are two things that to have be considered here.","start":676.826,"stop":685.58,"duration":8.75},{"text":"The Court has supervised jurisdiction over its own proceedings and let me say this, the Court, when it feels that there is been a lack of prosecution or want a prosecution that has the right to dismiss a case over a prosecution and I might say that there are many cases that hold that as well.","start":685.58,"stop":702.926,"duration":17.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose in this very case, prosecutor had command US Attorney to come in and to testify.","start":702.926,"stop":709.654,"duration":6.73},{"text":"Well, we have got a very large calendar in this district; we just do not have enough personnel, enough resources to put everything on as we might want as properly as you might want.","start":709.654,"stop":722.278,"duration":12.62},{"text":"We have to select out the most important and our exercise of our discretion, prosecutorial discretion, this case sat on the backgrounder for a while, will that be enough?","start":722.278,"stop":735.106,"duration":12.83}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"That bothers me, no, I think that would be enough to have it dismissed the reason that bothers me...","start":735.106,"stop":739.794,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You think you would still prevail it. That is the only (Voice Overlap).","start":739.794,"stop":743.081,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeha, I think so.","start":743.081,"stop":744.474,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But that is a practical matter, is not that true in many districts?","start":744.474,"stop":747.087,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"True, but what troubles me so much Justice Brennan, is that we now operate at the gun shot of the prosecutor, both courts and the defendants now.","start":747.087,"stop":757.431,"duration":10.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose a speedy trial well, might have a bearing out all…","start":757.431,"stop":760.59,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"That is what troubles me so much, Justice Rehnquist talked about the root cause, the delay in running this Assistant Attorney General, I might say that we now -- the prosecutor shoots the gun and now the courts have to get ready for trial within 60 days and defendants have to get ready for trial in 60 days.","start":760.59,"stop":782.722,"duration":22.13},{"text":"Now, we have judicial accountability that courts do and defendants and what the government wants to do, is remove all judicial accountability for their actions.","start":782.722,"stop":792.001,"duration":9.28}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But isn’t the speedy trial act going through the pressure on the government not to bring its indictments until it is sure that it is all ready to go to trial.","start":792.001,"stop":801.088,"duration":9.09},{"text":"Well, certainly because they are going to have all of their evidence, I think that is what they want to do, but I don’t…","start":801.088,"stop":804.983,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but the Justice Department did not sponsor the speedy trial.","start":804.983,"stop":809.145,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I understand, but I think there should be judicial accountability for their inaction inertia, I mean when we are accountable, courts and defendants, we have to jump at the women and at the trigger of the government.","start":809.145,"stop":824.34,"duration":15.2},{"text":"So, it seems to me that in view of the philosophy of the Speedy Trial Act and the policy statement of Congress and passing it, then we still…","start":824.34,"stop":832.378,"duration":8.04}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not sure what you mean by that, but I think if you look at the records, you would find that infinitely more cases are continued and postponed at the request of defendants by a ratio of 3-4 to 1; then are now continued and postponed with the request of the prosecution with the all parts.","start":832.378,"stop":847.658,"duration":15.28}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say this is probably true, but what is interesting here is that Lovasco kept calling the government saying “What you going to do?”","start":847.658,"stop":854.813,"duration":7.15},{"text":"This was not a man who sort of took off and thought that the whole matter was going to wash away and that nothing was going to happen to him, he is hoping for delay and all that sort of thing, he wanted the resolution.","start":854.813,"stop":865.987,"duration":11.17},{"text":"I would say certainly many defendants, people that are a guilty do not want a too broad trial, they do not want to go to jail.","start":865.987,"stop":871.386,"duration":5.4},{"text":"But I think people that are concerned about their innocence and people that are concerned about their anxiety systems and all that are concerned about some immediate resolutions for their problems.","start":871.386,"stop":882.947,"duration":11.56}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Gilden in the government’s brief, they make a second argument that the decision on that delay should have been made after trial rather than I advance of trial.","start":882.947,"stop":893.73,"duration":10.78},{"text":"Did they ask for this help -- did they ask the Court to postpone the decision?","start":893.73,"stop":897.157,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Never did, so this is merely an advisory opinion of asking this Court rule on, they never asked the court for the exercise of this discretion in delaying the matter until the close of the jury trial.","start":897.157,"stop":909.956,"duration":12.8}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you think about their suggestion as a procedure?","start":909.956,"stop":912.452,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I think that is a bad one, I feel that when you get into pre-acquisition delay and you raise the question of Fifth Amendment Due Process, how can you go to trial when you have lost very material evidence.","start":912.452,"stop":926.06,"duration":13.61},{"text":"I think the District Court has to make that determination before we go to trial.","start":926.06,"stop":930.919,"duration":4.86},{"text":"If you have lost your evidence and you have lost somebody who can prove your innocence and he finds that there is violation due process, it seems to me you cannot have a fair trial.","start":930.919,"stop":938.81,"duration":7.89},{"text":"I go though all that charade with a purpose and at the close of the trial have the court rule on whether or not you had a fair trial.","start":938.81,"stop":946.439,"duration":7.63},{"text":"It seems to me that you are saving two thing, you are saving the government certainly money for the trial, you are saving Judicial time and Judicial economy time with crowded dockets and you are certainly saving defendant a lot of counsel fees if he has ability to pay for a trial or case that might take two three four days or a week depending upon the circumstances.","start":946.439,"stop":965.894,"duration":19.46}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Once again Mr. Gilden what good is the statute of limitations.","start":965.894,"stop":970.176,"duration":4.28},{"text":"Rather what use is it?","start":970.176,"stop":972.54,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I might say that it is something the Court can be concerned about and I think it is something that as raised before I would say that the statute of limitations would be a factor in this matter had the government said anything at all.","start":972.54,"stop":987.749,"duration":15.21},{"text":"The government had come through with any evidence it was able to show that it is justifying its delay.","start":987.749,"stop":993.578,"duration":5.83}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"What part of the Constitution or statute tells the prosecuting attorney, that he must file his -- get his indictment within a certain number of months?","start":993.578,"stop":1002.382,"duration":8.8}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well there is nothing in the Constitution; there is nothing in any law except the statute of limitations.","start":1002.382,"stop":1006.405,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"How are you injured?","start":1006.405,"stop":1007.422,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"What sir?","start":1007.422,"stop":1008.122,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"How are you injured?","start":1008.122,"stop":1009.447,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"We are injured by the death of two witnesses.","start":1009.447,"stop":1012.932,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Who guarantees you those witnesses?","start":1012.932,"stop":1015.326,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well no one guarantees it but it is my burden to prove under Marion that I have been prejudiced, and I say that we assume that burden and satisfy the District Court that we had been prejudiced, and certainly that under Marion we are entitled to show they are prejudice.","start":1015.326,"stop":1034.136,"duration":18.81}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, you are entitled to show it but I wonder whether you entitle to win?","start":1034.136,"stop":1037.414,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I -- the District Court felt that I should -- what?","start":1037.414,"stop":1040.366,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"On the merits how many months do you think are necessary?","start":1040.366,"stop":1044.013,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not want to limit that…","start":1044.013,"stop":1044.906,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course you can because you can get a narcotics indictment in about 16 minutes and you can get involved in conspiracy indictment in about two years, right?","start":1044.906,"stop":1058.579,"duration":13.67}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"That is true.","start":1058.579,"stop":1059.573,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"So, there is no line to draw.","start":1059.573,"stop":1061.391,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that the District Court can analyze the type of case it can analyze whether it is a complex conspiracy case, it can analyze whether it is simple event like here, did he steal the guns or did not he steal the guns, that he know that they were stolen or didn't he, and I think that is a very simple proposition.","start":1061.391,"stop":1079.358,"duration":17.97}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Would the gravity of the offense play any part in the calculus you are suggesting, for example, typical state law there is no statute of limitations for murder.","start":1079.358,"stop":1090.795,"duration":11.44},{"text":"Whereas for ordinary theft larceny the statute the maybe three years, four years.","start":1090.795,"stop":1095.819,"duration":5.02},{"text":"Would you say that the government’s time could be longer depending on the seriousness of the offense?","start":1095.819,"stop":1101.504,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say certainly that a District Judge would certainly or a State Judge would certainly weigh very heavily dismissal of indictment based upon a murder alligation and I say that, that is something to be concerned about with respect to the exercise or discretion by the District Judge as to whether or not there was prejudicial delay in material prejudice to the defendant.","start":1101.504,"stop":1128.993,"duration":27.49},{"text":"I say that no one can setup standards as to this crime deserves, this amount of prejudicial delay and this one has had some another standard of time I think it is something for the District Court or the State Court to decide, within the framework of what is the delay, what was the reason for it and how was the defendant in anyway prejudiced by the delay.","start":1128.993,"stop":1149.889,"duration":20.9}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Gilden are behind in your criminal calendars in the eastern district?","start":1149.889,"stop":1153.709,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh! I think that we can get through trial within 60 days; we are not behind at all.","start":1153.709,"stop":1157.997,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Have you had many cases like this out there or emotions of this kind have been made.","start":1157.997,"stop":1162.042,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"One more a case called Barcait (ph) it was 48 months delay I believe and it went to the Eighth Circuit, it came out of Kansas city and what do you call that eastern district or the western.","start":1162.042,"stop":1174,"duration":11.96}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Both.","start":1174,"stop":1176.231,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"The District Judge in Kansas City dismissed the indictment for a 48 months delay and...","start":1176.231,"stop":1181.837,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Who was the judge on that one do you remember.","start":1181.837,"stop":1184.312,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"In the public court I think it was Judge Gibson who wrote the opinion.","start":1184.312,"stop":1192.157,"duration":7.85},{"text":"So, I would say that from what I know and what in crusing all the cases it is very unusual certainly for a District Judge to dismiss a case based on prejudicial delay and material result and prejudice.","start":1192.157,"stop":1206.859,"duration":14.7},{"text":"You will find that the courts are not receipted to that kind of reception to that kind of motion.","start":1206.859,"stop":1213.843,"duration":6.98},{"text":"So I think what we are saying here is that the government is certainly exercising a lot of concern about the administration of justice, but I do not think the Administration of Justice is going to be in anyway affected by decision of this Court, that the defendant was prejudice from the government did nothing to explain or justify its delay.","start":1213.843,"stop":1237.565,"duration":23.72}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rupp, do you have anything further?","start":1237.565,"stop":1241.376,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Couple of brief comments Mr. Chief Justice.","start":1241.376,"stop":1244.73,"duration":3.35},{"text":"Mr. Gilden suggest that if the government had done anything here perhaps this case should not be here, well then maybe it should not be here at the hearing on the motion to dismiss the United States Attorney in response to questions indicated that.","start":1244.73,"stop":1257.759,"duration":13.03},{"text":"Furthermore as to additional witnesses received that to the date of September 26, 1973 that is true, that is there were few additional witnesses discovered, but not as to the investigation itself.","start":1257.759,"stop":1268.633,"duration":10.87},{"text":"The Eight Circuit expressly credited that representation and none of the less held that the indictment in this case should be dismissed finding that that was not a sufficient justification for the 18 months delay that occurred here.","start":1268.633,"stop":1280.444,"duration":11.81},{"text":"Mr. Justice Stevens, as I recall yesterday you expressed some concern about having government counsel testify routinely in response to motion such as respondents.","start":1280.444,"stop":1288.928,"duration":8.48},{"text":"I should point out that that is a much greater problem under the Eighth Circuit's formulation than under what we believe the Due Process Clause means.","start":1288.928,"stop":1296.871,"duration":7.94},{"text":"Whenever the defendant, under the Eighth Circuit’s formulation has been able to make a facially credible allegation of prejudice, the Eighth Circuit would have the government come in an attempt to formatively to justify any delay that occurred.","start":1296.871,"stop":1309.059,"duration":12.19},{"text":"The only way that could be done is by having the United States Attorney or the Assistant United States Attorney come in, attempt the document, the course of the investigation at detail, saying who was doing what at what time for what reasons.","start":1309.059,"stop":1322.601,"duration":13.54},{"text":"Government counsel might also have to take the stand under the view of the under the Due Process Clause as we believe it should be construed, but the enquiry would be much more limited.","start":1322.601,"stop":1333.118,"duration":10.52},{"text":"Government counsel already takes the stand in a number of contexts for example the one that most readily comes to mind, are motions that deal with some aspect to pre-bargaining negotiations.","start":1333.118,"stop":1344.346,"duration":11.23},{"text":"With respect to the questions that you asked yesterday Mr. Justice Marshall, the government's position is not that a potential defendant has an obligation to ask to be indicted, he may of course do nothing.","start":1344.346,"stop":1357.154,"duration":12.81},{"text":"The question here is under what circumstances a defendant is entitled to come into court and say guilty or not, the Due Process Clause prevents the government from trying me.","start":1357.154,"stop":1368.558,"duration":11.4},{"text":"Now, we have suggested that the defendant may make the records showing in any of several ways and all my response to your question yesterday was intended to indicate is that, if a defendant, a potential defendant had indicated that if the government delayed in reaching a decision whether to prosecute, he might be prejudiced, he would be in a stronger position to claim immunity from prosecution.","start":1368.558,"stop":1391.022,"duration":22.46}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is not it true that he did in this case? Is that true or not?","start":1391.022,"stop":1395.107,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"The record is a bit unclear, the record certainly is clear that Mr. Lovasco called the Postal Inspector on several occasions, now the record indicates…","start":1395.107,"stop":1402.523,"duration":7.42}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, isn’t that to answer to my question?","start":1402.523,"stop":1405.078,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"That he had no time.","start":1405.078,"stop":1407.612,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That he did do it.","start":1407.612,"stop":1408.707,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think the record is precisely the contrary, that what the record shows is that Mr. Lovasco said when he was interviewed that he had -- the only guns he had sold or guns he had found in the back seat of his car, not until the motion on the hearing to dismiss, did he mention and then for the first time, that there were two additional people, Stewart and his brother and that the guns in fact were at least two or three of them came from some other source.","start":1408.707,"stop":1434.178,"duration":25.47}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you say, he never called the prosecutor and says, “Why do not you do some about this case?”","start":1434.178,"stop":1442.206,"duration":8.03}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"He did not call the prosecutor, he called the Postal Inspector, I think it is a same difference…","start":1442.206,"stop":1445.499,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, like the government.","start":1445.499,"stop":1446.697,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that is right.","start":1446.697,"stop":1447.151,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he did do that.","start":1447.151,"stop":1448.252,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"He did, but he did not say anything that we…","start":1448.252,"stop":1449.475,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn’t that what you wanted him to do?","start":1449.475,"stop":1451.684,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"No, he did not.","start":1451.684,"stop":1452.761,"duration":1.08},{"text":"What he did is to say, “I assume, I am anxious about this,” what he did not do is give the government any cause to believe, that he was about to be prejudiced, his ability to defend himself the trial would be prejudiced when any delay would occur.","start":1452.761,"stop":1465.537,"duration":12.78}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he certainly could not have told him that I am afraid that Mr. Stewart is going to die.","start":1465.537,"stop":1470.943,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"He could not have said that because he had said earlier that he had found all of the guns he had sold to Boa as in the back seat of his car.","start":1470.943,"stop":1479.794,"duration":8.85}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rupp before you sit down, your opponent has said that in the lower courts, the government took the position that all of the defendant need to show as prejudice and unreasonable delay. Has he correctly characterized the record?","start":1479.794,"stop":1489.794,"duration":10}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"That is incorrect Your Honor.","start":1489.794,"stop":1493.543,"duration":3.75},{"text":"As I indicated during my presentation yesterday, the District Court and again, I can only refer you to the District Court’s order.","start":1493.543,"stop":1500.563,"duration":7.02},{"text":"The District Court based its dismissal in this case on Rule 48 of Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure.","start":1500.563,"stop":1505.24,"duration":4.68},{"text":"To some extent that is cued the proceedings during the opening round of briefs in the Court of Appeals.","start":1505.24,"stop":1512.277,"duration":7.04},{"text":"The issues presented here though were argued to the Court of Appeals and then when the Court of Appeals issued its decisions, the government petitioned for rehearing, arguing both, the issues that we present here precisely as we present them here and arguing that the District Court should have delayed reaching a decision till after trial.","start":1512.277,"stop":1534.642,"duration":22.37},{"text":"The reason that was not done earlier is that the motion itself was especially inadequate.","start":1534.642,"stop":1539.384,"duration":4.74},{"text":"The motion does not contain an assertion that Lovasco would have been prejudiced to trial.","start":1539.384,"stop":1546.79,"duration":7.41},{"text":"It only claimed the anxiety in concern and an unelaborated assertion of prejudice.","start":1546.79,"stop":1551.368,"duration":4.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rupp I asked to you that argument of part two of your brief, that you just discussed that the -- when a trial judge is met with the motion of this kind by the defendant, that he should differ ruling on until after trial, you mean after verdict or in case of all the evidence, which is unclear to me?","start":1551.368,"stop":1573.421,"duration":22.05}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Actually it could come at either point, there was certainly is…","start":1573.421,"stop":1576.158,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it could come certainly as it could come before trial, but what is your argument?","start":1576.158,"stop":1580.315,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court is satisfied after having heard the evidence that the defendant has suffered materiel prejudice in once to avoid, having a verdict to return which may cause some prejudice, I think that’s appropriate.","start":1580.315,"stop":1592.729,"duration":12.41},{"text":"Our real concern here is having these motions disposed off and particularly the prejudice aspect to the motion disposed off, before trial of the general issue, before the Court has a real opportunity to know precisely what this case is about.","start":1592.729,"stop":1605.747,"duration":13.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I understand your reasoning, what is your argument before or after verdict.","start":1605.747,"stop":1610.313,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Our position is that if the Court is satisfied before the verdict, that the defendant is been prejudiced; we fairly can appropriately dismiss the indictment at that point and not...","start":1610.313,"stop":1618.242,"duration":7.93}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though the Jury might acquit it…","start":1618.242,"stop":1619.868,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Acquit it, even though the Jury might acquit it…","start":1619.868,"stop":1622.151,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"And even though if you appeal from the dismissal before verdict and the Court of Appeals besides your own, then you may not be able to prosecute a man because that is double jeopardy.","start":1622.151,"stop":1630.537,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that is a problem, alright I am sorry, let me amend that.","start":1630.537,"stop":1632.503,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be a double jeopardy problem.","start":1632.503,"stop":1634.184,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes that is right and I am sorry.","start":1634.184,"stop":1636.304,"duration":2.12},{"text":"That would present a problem, if the Court would rule on…","start":1636.304,"stop":1639.414,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"So, that has prompted my question.","start":1639.414,"stop":1641.419,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and I am sorry.","start":1641.419,"stop":1642.762,"duration":1.34},{"text":"Our position then would be that he should wait until as we indicated in the brief after the verdict is returned and before judgment is been entered on the brief.","start":1642.762,"stop":1648.744,"duration":5.98}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that is what Marion seems to contemplate.","start":1648.744,"stop":1650.552,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"That is precisely what Marion seems to contemplate.","start":1650.552,"stop":1653.994,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":1653.994,"stop":1655.19,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you gentlemen.","start":1655.19,"stop":1655.824,"duration":0.63},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":1655.824,"stop":1657.452,"duration":1.63}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 21, 1977","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger6/oral_argument_audio/17318","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Chief Justice Rehnquist: We’ll hear arguments next in 1844, United States against Lovasco.","start":0,"stop":38.712,"duration":38.71},{"text":"Mr. Rupp, I think you may proceed.","start":38.712,"stop":43.182,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":43.182,"stop":47.611,"duration":4.43},{"text":"The Government petitioned for a Writ of Certiorari in this case after a divided panel of the Court of Appeals for the Eight Circuit had affirmed the dismissal of three counts of the indictment.","start":47.611,"stop":57.745,"duration":10.13},{"text":"Unlike the District Court, the Court of Appeals based its decision on the Due Process Clause of the Fifth Amendment, holding that Respondent had satisfied with the majority characterized as the two basic elements essential to a claim of impermissible pre-accusation delay, unreasonableness on the part of the Government and prejudice to his ability to defend against the charges.","start":57.745,"stop":81.538,"duration":23.79},{"text":"Because we believe the decision in this case to be incorrect and because that decision conflicts with the approach taken by several other Courts of Appeals on two reoccurring issues of substantial importance, we sought further review by this Court.","start":81.538,"stop":94.063,"duration":12.53},{"text":"I should like to begin this afternoon by outlining as briefly as I can the context in which the issues presented here arose.","start":94.063,"stop":104.039,"duration":9.98},{"text":"Respondent was indicted on March 6th, 1975 on three counts of unlawful possession of materials stolen from the mails and one count of dealing in firearms without a license.","start":104.039,"stop":117.669,"duration":13.63},{"text":"The indictment referred specifically to eight handguns that Respondent allegedly had processed and sold between July 25th and August 31st, 1973.","start":117.669,"stop":129.293,"duration":11.62},{"text":"Six days after his indictment, Respondent moved under Rule 48 of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure and the Sixth Amendment to have the charges against him dismissed.","start":129.293,"stop":138.402,"duration":9.11},{"text":"He alleged in that motion that the Government had not obtained any information relating to the charges in the indictment after September of 1973, that the ensuing delay of approximately 18 months was unreasonable, that that delay had caused him to experience anxiety and concern.","start":138.402,"stop":159.742,"duration":21.34},{"text":"He did not claim that the delay had impaired his ability to defend against the charges.","start":159.742,"stop":165.584,"duration":5.84},{"text":"The parties stipulated at the outset of the hearing held on the motion to dismiss that a Postal Inspector had interviewed Respondent in September of 1973 about a series of thefts from the Terminal Railroad Association facility in St. Louis.","start":165.584,"stop":181.472,"duration":15.89},{"text":"The parties also stipulated that investigation of the thefts had continued thereafter, but that the Government had discovered only one witness after September of 1973 who might have bolstered its case.","start":181.472,"stop":197.207,"duration":15.73},{"text":"Respondent attempted to support his claim that the Government had possessed sufficient evidence as of September of 1973 to warrant presenting that evidence to the grand jury by introducing a report that had been prepared by the Postal Inspector.","start":197.207,"stop":212.145,"duration":14.94},{"text":"That report described a series of purchases of semiautomatic handguns from two men in August and September of 1973, all of which had been stolen after mailing from the Terminal Railroad Association in St. Louis.","start":212.145,"stop":227.295,"duration":15.15},{"text":"The report stated that the agents had traced the weapons to a man named Joe Boaz (ph) and that Boaz had admitted that he had obtained the weapons from Respondent.","start":227.295,"stop":239.297,"duration":12},{"text":"The report further indicated that the Postal Inspector had interviewed Respondent in the presence of Respondent’s attorney on September 26th, 1973.","start":239.297,"stop":248.03,"duration":8.73},{"text":"Respondent, who was then working as a switchman at the Terminal Railroad Association and would not have had access to insured mail parcels in the normal course of his duties, admitted to the Postal Inspector that he had sold Boaz four or five weapons.","start":248.03,"stop":262.609,"duration":14.58},{"text":"Respondent attempted to explain his possession on those guns by claiming that he had found them in a sack in the backseat of his automobile after having gone to the Terminal Railroad Association to visit his son, who worked there as a mail handler.","start":262.609,"stop":276.865,"duration":14.26},{"text":"The report noted finally that although Respondent’s son had cashed four or five of the checks given by Boaz as payment for the guns, the Postal Inspectors had no direct evidence that Respondent’s son was responsible for the thefts.","start":276.865,"stop":293.14,"duration":16.27},{"text":"Respondent testified at the hearing on the Motion to Dismiss that two possible witnesses on his behalf had died during the 18-month delay referred to in his motion, his brother and a man named Tom Stewart.","start":293.14,"stop":306.502,"duration":13.36},{"text":"According to Respondent, his brother had died approximately one year before the hearing, had worked at the same place of business as Boaz and had been present when he had made arrangements by telephone to sell the guns to Boaz.","start":306.502,"stop":319.71,"duration":13.21},{"text":"Respondent claimed that Stewart was his source for two or three of the guns and that Stewart had died approximately six months before the hearing; again, however, Respondent stated that he had not disclosed -- or, Respondent stated for the first time, rather, that he had not disclosed Stewart’s involvement earlier because of fear of retaliation from Stewart.","start":319.71,"stop":341.502,"duration":21.79},{"text":"Respondent’s testimony obviously raised a number of questions.","start":341.502,"stop":346.251,"duration":4.75},{"text":"For example, the fact that Respondent had told the Postal Inspector that he had sold Boaz only the guns he had found at the backseat of his car and no more was inconsistent with his assertion at the hearing that he had obtained two or three of those guns from Stewart.","start":346.251,"stop":361.6,"duration":15.35},{"text":"Similarly, fear of retaliation from Stewart could hardly have accounted for Respondent’s failure to mention at the time he filed his Motion to Dismiss Stewart’s involvement, since according to Respondent Stewart had been dead at that time for approximately six months; and furthermore, at no time during the hearing on the Motion to Dismiss did Respondent indicate what exculpatory testimony his brother or Stewart might have provided.","start":361.6,"stop":387.409,"duration":25.81},{"text":"Despite these problems, the District Court dismissed all counts of the indictment.","start":387.409,"stop":391.882,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Who was the Judge, Mr. …","start":391.882,"stop":393.964,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Judge Reagan.","start":393.964,"stop":396.596,"duration":2.63},{"text":"The Court based its dismissal on Rule 48 of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure, finding that the Government had not adequately justified the 18-month delay referred to in the Motion to Dismiss and that Respondent had been prejudiced by the death of Tom Stewart, whom the Court characterized as a material witness on his behalf.","start":396.596,"stop":415.46,"duration":18.86},{"text":"A divided panel of the Court of Appeals affirmed dismissal of the possession counts and reversed dismissal of the count of the indictment charging Respondent with having dealt in firearms without a license.","start":415.46,"stop":427.074,"duration":11.61},{"text":"Although the majority credited the Government’s explanation for the delay as stemming from an effort on its part to discover persons in addition to Respondent who may have been responsible for the thefts, the majority nevertheless concluded that the Government had not sufficiently justified the delay and then that delay was, therefore, unreasonable.","start":427.074,"stop":449.193,"duration":22.12},{"text":"The Court also accepted the District Court’s finding that Respondent had been prejudiced by the death of Tom Stewart, adding without any basis that were Stewart’s testimony available, it would have supported Respondent’s claim that he did not know that the guns had been stolen from the mails.","start":449.193,"stop":465.761,"duration":16.57},{"text":"It may be worth mentioning, since Respondent has raised the matter, at least briefly, that there is no impediment to this Court’s reaching the issues presented in the Petition.","start":465.761,"stop":474.01,"duration":8.25},{"text":"It is true that the thrust of the Government’s opening brief on appeal was not directed at those issues; but the reason for that was that the District Court had based its decision not on the Fifth Amendment, but on Rule 48 of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure, which of course is not applicable to the pre-accusatory phase of criminal proceedings.","start":474.01,"stop":491.379,"duration":17.37},{"text":"Perhaps more importantly, as the opinions in this case made clear, the panel expressly considered the issues presented to this Court, relying ultimately upon a view of the Due Process Clause that the Government disputed on rehearing in that court and disputes before this Court.","start":491.379,"stop":509.579,"duration":18.2},{"text":"The decision in this case imposes upon the Government, via the Due Process Clause of the Fifth Amendment, a duty of speedy accusation roughly equivalent to -- in some respects, more stringent than -- the speedy-trial obligations specifically imposed by the Sixth Amendment.","start":509.579,"stop":527.049,"duration":17.47},{"text":"The standard employed here for measuring the permissibility of pre-accusation delay cannot be squared with this Court’s decision in Marion.","start":527.049,"stop":534.713,"duration":7.66},{"text":"Indeed, it renders that decision largely meaningless.","start":534.713,"stop":538.593,"duration":3.88},{"text":"Our position with respect to cases of this sort remains what it was at the time Marion was decided:  that is, that the Due Process Clause is not violated by delay in the institution of formal criminal proceedings unless that delay was part of an effort on the Government’s part to prejudice the defense or perhaps, alternatively, was engaged in by the Government in reckless disregard of known risks of prejudice to the defense and actually caused such prejudice.","start":538.593,"stop":568.466,"duration":29.87},{"text":"At the heart of the decision in Marion was this Court’s conclusion that the disabilities suffered by potential defendants did not, in the vast majority of cases, begin to compare with the disabilities suffered by those who are actual defendants.","start":568.466,"stop":584.086,"duration":15.62},{"text":"The potential defendant is not required to live under the stigma that almost inevitably attends formal public accusation.","start":584.086,"stop":592.312,"duration":8.23},{"text":"The differences were even more dramatic in the case of defendants who are incarcerated prior to trial.","start":592.312,"stop":599.99,"duration":7.68},{"text":"Unlike the pre-accusatory period, furthermore, delaying formal accusation until the Government has completed its investigation may benefit the defendant and society in a variety of ways.","start":599.99,"stop":614.456,"duration":14.47},{"text":"Investigation beyond the point of mere probable cause, for example, may result in the discovery of evidence exculpating the defendant, thereby avoiding unwarranted or ill-considered charges of criminal conduct.","start":614.456,"stop":627.908,"duration":13.45},{"text":"It may lead to the discovery of ameliorating evidence and a discretionary decision not to prosecute.","start":627.908,"stop":634.711,"duration":6.8},{"text":"It may lead to the discovery of evidence indicating that the person originally under suspicion probably also committed other crimes or that additional persons were involved, thus facilitating the resolution of related charges against all in a single proceeding.","start":634.711,"stop":651.026,"duration":16.31},{"text":"It is often made possible the shortening of the time between formal accusation and trial.","start":651.026,"stop":658.386,"duration":7.36},{"text":"These interests are far from insubstantial.","start":658.386,"stop":661.865,"duration":3.48},{"text":"They cannot be ignored in assessing the scope of the Government’s duty under the Due Process Clause.","start":661.865,"stop":667.912,"duration":6.05},{"text":"It is an exceedingly serious matter to immunize from trial one whom the Government has reason to believe is guilty of criminal conduct.","start":667.912,"stop":678.387,"duration":10.47},{"text":"A remedy so stringent in our judgment should be reserved for those cases of affirmative governmental misconduct.","start":678.387,"stop":685.102,"duration":6.72},{"text":"That is not to say that the Due Process Clause is never violated without proof of affirmative governmental misconduct; Brady and Agers stand to the contrary.","start":685.102,"stop":695.599,"duration":10.5},{"text":"But the remedy for violation of the Government’s duty to provide the defense with exculpatory testimony in a Brady or Agers context is not the very stringent remedy of dismissing all charges, immunizing the defendant from further prosecution, but remanding the case for a new trial.","start":695.599,"stop":713.713,"duration":18.11},{"text":"I want to emphasize here as clearly as I can that so long as formal accusation is delayed pending further investigation, as it was in this case, we believe that delay can never be considered unjustified, should never be held to constitute a breach of the Government’s duties to a particular defendant.","start":713.713,"stop":733.754,"duration":20.04},{"text":"As Mr. Justice Powell pointed out in Watson, “Good police practice often requires postponing an arrest, even after probable cause has been established, in order to develop further evidence to prove guilt to a jury”; Hoffa is to the same effect.","start":733.754,"stop":747.997,"duration":14.24},{"text":"As Mr. Justice Stewart has stated for the Court in that case:  “Law enforcement officers are under no constitutional duty to call a halt to a criminal investigation the moment they have the minimum evidence to establish probable cause, a quantum of evidence, which may fall far short of the amount necessary to establish guilt to a jury.”","start":747.997,"stop":770.55,"duration":22.55},{"text":"We do not mean to suggest, however, that the public policies making delay in the institution of formal criminal proceedings, an inevitable and desirable part of the criminal process, necessarily eliminates all concern with the expeditious enforcement of the criminal laws.","start":770.55,"stop":788.137,"duration":17.59},{"text":"There may be times -- hopefully, they will be rare -- when delay in formal accusation is the result of efforts on the Government’s part to prejudice the defense and such prejudice occurs. There may also be times -- we hope equally rare -- when the Government engages in delay in reckless disregard of known risks of prejudice to the defense and such prejudice occurs.","start":788.137,"stop":813.468,"duration":25.33},{"text":"As we acknowledged in Marion, the Due Process Clause is available to remedy abuses of those sorts, which injures society, as well as the criminal accused.","start":813.468,"stop":823.846,"duration":10.38},{"text":"But in other than those rare cases, we do not believe that the Due Process Clause requires courts to consider the timeliness, on an ad-hoc basis, of criminal charges brought within the applicable statute of limitations.","start":823.846,"stop":838.895,"duration":15.05},{"text":"As this Court pointed out in Untied States v. Ewell:  “Statutes of limitation stand as the primary guarantee against the bringing of overly stale criminal charges.”","start":838.895,"stop":849.487,"duration":10.59},{"text":"They represent a legislative balancing of society’s interest in equitable law enforcement and the interests of potential defendants in being freed from having to defend themselves against charges of long-past criminal conduct.","start":849.487,"stop":863.645,"duration":14.16},{"text":"To be sure, statutes of limitation were never intended to immunize from judicial scrutiny prosecutorial misconduct, however unfair, occurring within the applicable limitations’ period; but they do take into account the fact that the timing of decisions to prosecute should be or necessarily are affected both by the need to proceed with care and deliberateness and by a variety of institutional factors; the need to assign priorities, for example, to the prosecution of some cases rather than others.","start":863.645,"stop":897.848,"duration":34.2},{"text":"A standard for measuring the permissibility of pre-accusation delay, such as that employed here, would involve the courts in the same process in which Congress is engaged in enacting statutes of limitation.","start":897.848,"stop":911.157,"duration":13.31},{"text":"More importantly, we believe the courts should avoid the kind of ad-hoc inquiry into the permissibility of pre-accusation delay that was engaged in here for a variety of eminently practical considerations.","start":911.157,"stop":926.655,"duration":15.5},{"text":"First, if the standard in this case were to be used widely, courts would be required in perhaps the majority of cases to attempt to determine the point at which the Government was obligated to take its case to the grand jury.","start":926.655,"stop":942.964,"duration":16.31},{"text":"Whether measured against the standard of probable cause or some other standard, a determination of that sort would involve nearly insuperable problems of proof.","start":942.964,"stop":953.447,"duration":10.48},{"text":"Second, it would make little sense if the duty as so conceived were limited to Government prosecutors.","start":953.447,"stop":961.908,"duration":8.46},{"text":"If the Due Process Clause is construed as embodying a prompt accusation requirement, that duty presumably would extend to Government investigators generally.","start":961.908,"stop":976.133,"duration":14.23},{"text":"We believe that judicial efforts to supervise the conduct of criminal investigations by reviewing them at the behest of individual defendants would have very serious import for the administration of criminal justice.","start":976.133,"stop":993.217,"duration":17.08},{"text":"Third, a prompt-accusation requirement would necessitate the holding of lengthy hearings, trial before the trial, in almost every case before the required determinations could be made with any assurance.","start":993.217,"stop":1006.561,"duration":13.34},{"text":"The prosecutor would have to document in detail the course of the investigation leading to the charges, and particularly if the hearing were held before the trial of the general issue, the prosecutor would have to provide a dress rehearsal of his case in an effort to show that the time consumed by the investigation was reasonable under the circumstances.","start":1006.561,"stop":1026.632,"duration":20.07},{"text":"At the same time, the courts would be required to attempt to resolve in the context of the particular case a variety of essentially policy disputes that transcend the individual case, whether available prosecutorial resources were appropriately devoted to the prosecution in one matter rather than another, whether the importance of continuing an agent in an undercover capacity was more important than proceeding with the prosecution of the particular defendant whose involvement was known.","start":1026.632,"stop":1057.707,"duration":31.08},{"text":"It is no answer to suggest that delay for any of these reasons is avoidable and is therefore chargeable to the Government.","start":1057.707,"stop":1065.986,"duration":8.28},{"text":"In fact, they are relevant to determining under the Due Process Clause whether, in light of all the circumstances, the Government has proceeded consistently with shared notions of fair play and fundamental decency.","start":1065.986,"stop":1079.784,"duration":13.8},{"text":"We thus submit that the courts below erred in dismissing three counts of the indictment in this case on the basis of pre-accusation delay.","start":1079.784,"stop":1089.131,"duration":9.35},{"text":"The indictment was returned within 20 months of the offenses charged, well within the applicable five-year statute of limitations.","start":1089.131,"stop":1097.108,"duration":7.98},{"text":"Respondent neither alleged nor sought to show that the Government had delayed in order to gain an impermissible tactical advantage.","start":1097.108,"stop":1104.994,"duration":7.89},{"text":"Neither has Respondent ever suggested that the Government proceeded in reckless disregard of known risks of prejudice to him.","start":1104.994,"stop":1113.492,"duration":8.5}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rupp, at that point, do you feel what you have just said now should be the burden of the defendant?","start":1113.492,"stop":1119.836,"duration":6.34}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I do, Mr. Justice Blackmun.","start":1119.836,"stop":1121.17,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, isn’t this material that is specifically within the control and knowledge and awareness of the Government?","start":1121.17,"stop":1130.562,"duration":9.39}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"The first standard, the standard that we specifically suggested in Marion, the prosecutorial-misconduct standard, is to some extent a subjective test, and the evidence that would be needed to sustain it, at least to some extent, would be within the hands of the government, although the United States Attorneys or Assistant United States Attorneys responsible for delay could be, and I assume would be, called to the stand and asked to explain the reasons for the delay. I don’t think that we can assume that Government counsel would not answer those questions candidly.","start":1130.562,"stop":1167.465,"duration":36.9},{"text":"The second alternative, or perhaps supplemental standard, is a good deal more objective, the Government proceeding with known risks of prejudice to the defendant.","start":1167.465,"stop":1180.251,"duration":12.79},{"text":"Now, that standard and the evidence needed to sustain a case under that standard would not necessarily be within the exclusive control of the Government.","start":1180.251,"stop":1190.676,"duration":10.42},{"text":"If, for example, a defendant had communicated, as this Respondent did not, that evidence in his possession needed for any defense he might have to put on was disappearing and the Government, despite that knowledge, proceeded to delay or continued to delay, such evidence would go a long way toward making out a case.","start":1190.676,"stop":1215.878,"duration":25.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rupp, may I follow up on Mr. Justice Blackmun’s question?","start":1215.878,"stop":1219.99,"duration":4.11},{"text":"I wonder if you have given sufficient consideration to your answer that the Government prosecutor would readily take the stand in discovery in connection with such a pre-trial motion.","start":1219.99,"stop":1230.189,"duration":10.2},{"text":"Is that a considered position of the Government or one you just felt was an appropriate answer to a question you might not have thought through?","start":1230.189,"stop":1236.468,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I have not discussed it with others.","start":1236.468,"stop":1238.722,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Because that would be a rather dramatic departure from what I understand the normal practice of prosecutors to be if they are asked to testify about their investigation of charges and the like.","start":1238.722,"stop":1248.929,"duration":10.21}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I certainly am prepared to go back to the Justice Department and obtain the Government’s position.","start":1248.929,"stop":1256.225,"duration":7.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In fact, it’s my concern about the undesirability of such discovery and that type of practice that makes me question the wisdom of the test that the Government advances in this particular case.","start":1256.225,"stop":1267.184,"duration":10.96}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in this case, Government counsel entered into with Respondent a stipulation which encompassed these matters.","start":1267.184,"stop":1279.894,"duration":12.71},{"text":"I would assume that in many cases, such factors could be stipulated to.","start":1279.894,"stop":1286.966,"duration":7.07},{"text":"Now, the governmental-misconduct standard, we fully anticipate that the case will be exceedingly rare in which Government counsel has affirmatively engaged in the kind of misconduct we think alone would violate the Due Process Clause.","start":1286.966,"stop":1302.576,"duration":15.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I must confess that although the words sound persuasive when you give them, I have some difficulty thinking of concrete examples that fit your test.","start":1302.576,"stop":1312.276,"duration":9.7},{"text":"I mean, Government normally, I suppose, wants to convict people it believes are guilty of crimes, and what is the kind of misconduct that might justify saying that --","start":1312.276,"stop":1321.981,"duration":9.7}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, perhaps all of the conduct that might be encompassed under the governmental-misconduct standard would be also be encompassed -- I think it probably would be encompassed -- within the standard of proceeding in view of known risks of prejudice to the defense.","start":1321.981,"stop":1337.79,"duration":15.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, supposing a witness, one of the witnesses, is an elderly man.","start":1337.79,"stop":1341.124,"duration":3.33},{"text":"The Government believes he is going to testify falsely to an alibi, falsely.","start":1341.124,"stop":1345.315,"duration":4.19},{"text":"They are satisfied the crime was committed as alleged.","start":1345.315,"stop":1348.16,"duration":2.85},{"text":"If they delayed a couple of months because they thought he might not be available as a witness when he was going be a false witness, would that justify a dismissal of indictment?","start":1348.16,"stop":1364.318,"duration":16.16}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"The elderly gentleman is not the defendant, but a witness or a prospective witness in the case.","start":1364.318,"stop":1376.852,"duration":12.53},{"text":"I suppose it would, and the reason is that it will seldom be true that the Government will know with 100% assurance that the anticipated testimony of a witness is going to be false.","start":1376.852,"stop":1394.817,"duration":17.96},{"text":"That is a decision to be made by the jury, and if the Government is 98% sure that someone is going to testify falsely and it will be difficult to overcome that testimony and it proceeds to delay with the full intent to prosecute at some later time when that witness may not be available, I think that that’s the kind of governmental misconduct the standard would encompass.","start":1394.817,"stop":1420.077,"duration":25.26},{"text":"But I also think that it would be encompassed by proceeding the risk alternative formulation; that is, the Government proceeding, despite its knowledge that the defendant suffers a very real chance of being prejudiced by any delay.","start":1420.077,"stop":1440.351,"duration":20.27},{"text":"Now, in the event the defendant’s evidence is, in fact, in a process, evidence that the defendant feels is needed is in the process of disappearing, one of the things he can do, of course, is to contact the United States Attorney and inform him of that fact.","start":1440.351,"stop":1457.515,"duration":17.16},{"text":"In this case, Respondent could hardly have claimed that the Government proceeded recklessly with respect to the two witnesses he testified at the hearing would have been available earlier.","start":1457.515,"stop":1468.58,"duration":11.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I understand you correctly, you think it’s the criminal’s responsibility to insist that he be indicted?","start":1468.58,"stop":1479.687,"duration":11.11}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"No, of course, not.","start":1479.687,"stop":1481.013,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what is it you’re talking about? You said he should get in touch with the prosecutor.","start":1481.013,"stop":1487.01,"duration":6}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"A conversation of that sort might go something as follows:  “I am innocent” --","start":1487.01,"stop":1492.3,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I can’t find anyplace in the Constitution that puts a burden on a man to get indicted.","start":1492.3,"stop":1497.878,"duration":5.58}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"We are not suggesting for the moment that the Respondent here have called the United State Attorney and said, ”Indict me.”","start":1497.878,"stop":1504.241,"duration":6.36},{"text":"What Respondent might have done is to say that, “I am innocent, the evidence or some of the evidence I need to establish my innocence may not be available at some point in the future; but if you are ever going to indict me, indict me now”.","start":1504.241,"stop":1517.73,"duration":13.49}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He doesn’t need to establish his innocence; he is innocent.","start":1517.73,"stop":1521.293,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"To defend against the charges.","start":1521.293,"stop":1522.569,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He is innocent until he is convicted.","start":1522.569,"stop":1524.52,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, he is.","start":1524.52,"stop":1525.327,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And he is certainly innocent until he is indicted.","start":1525.327,"stop":1528.338,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, that’s true.","start":1528.338,"stop":1529.336,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah, but this Court doesn’t have to overturn any conviction which is achieved by a jury on a charge of tactics such as were made in this case unless it’s satisfied it’s in the interests of justice to do so, too.","start":1529.336,"stop":1541.779,"duration":12.44}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1541.779,"stop":1543.402,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But, I don’t …","start":1543.402,"stop":1544.456,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any case in this Court that says it’s a responsibility of a person allegedly about to be charged with a crime to get in touch with the U.S. Attorney?","start":1544.456,"stop":1555.156,"duration":10.7}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"No, and we are not contending for that for the moment.","start":1555.156,"stop":1560.543,"duration":5.39},{"text":"The Government, for example, may learn from third parties wholly unrelated to the defense that there was some risk of evidence relevant to the case -- that there were some risk that evidence relevant to the case is about to be lost.","start":1560.543,"stop":1573.294,"duration":12.75},{"text":"If the Government nonetheless proceeds to delay and it could proceed, that would in our judgment fall under the tests that we’re contending for here.","start":1573.294,"stop":1583.916,"duration":10.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And how would the defendant find out that the Government had that information?","start":1583.916,"stop":1592.51,"duration":8.59}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Presumably, it would come from third parties associated with the case.","start":1592.51,"stop":1597.05,"duration":4.54},{"text":"In the vast majority of the cases, those people will be as accessible to the defendant as they will be to the Government and, often, more accessible to the defendant.","start":1597.05,"stop":1607.098,"duration":10.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t understand it at all, why this responsibility is on the person that’s about to be indicted to come forward and say, ”You know, I am about to be indicted, and I wish you’d hurry up”.","start":1607.098,"stop":1619.087,"duration":11.99}]},{"speakerName":"John P. Rupp","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, again, we are not suggesting that a defendant put pressure on the Government to indict him.","start":1619.087,"stop":1625.723,"duration":6.64},{"text":"What the defendant might do is suggest that evidence relevant to his defense is about to be lost; and again, that evidence can come from third parties and is going to be the rare case in which the Government engages in such misconduct.","start":1625.723,"stop":1641.278,"duration":15.56},{"text":"I would like to reserve the balance and my time, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":1641.278,"stop":1651.57,"duration":10.29}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Gilden.","start":1651.57,"stop":1653.345,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court, I do want to clarify a few statements the solicitor has made which I don’t think are not borne out in the record.","start":1653.345,"stop":1662.264,"duration":8.92},{"text":"Judge Reagan did not decide this case under Rule 48, Justice Blackmun.","start":1662.264,"stop":1666.265,"duration":4},{"text":"He decided it merely on Fifth Amendment, the essentials as set forth in Marion that there was pre-indictment delay and subsequent prejudice to the defendant.","start":1666.265,"stop":1674.613,"duration":8.35},{"text":"I might say the Government has made all kinds of arguments about why they did not win this motion, and that’s what they are confronted with today.","start":1674.613,"stop":1684.188,"duration":9.58},{"text":"And Justice Marshall, when I talk about we should … the defendant has to give up all of his evidence to the Government and tell the Government what his case is going to be is sort of silly and nonsense, it’s contrary to law.","start":1684.188,"stop":1696.72,"duration":12.53},{"text":"When the defendant came in with his witnesses to the trial court in the pretrial motion, he presented his evidence that two of his witnesses had died.","start":1696.72,"stop":1705.445,"duration":8.72},{"text":"I know nothing in any kind of law in this country that says that a defendant has to signal his testimony to the Government about what his evidence was going to be.","start":1705.445,"stop":1714.198,"duration":8.75},{"text":"The Government at no time asked for a delay.","start":1714.198,"stop":1719.769,"duration":5.57},{"text":"They didn’t ask for a continuance to check out the veracity of the defendant’s statement to the Court.","start":1719.769,"stop":1725.297,"duration":5.53},{"text":"They never said, “We don’t believe these two witnesses died and, therefore, we want to check it out and see whether or not they would support your statement, they would exculpate you in the commission of this crime of possession of stolen mail matter”.","start":1725.297,"stop":1738.888,"duration":13.59},{"text":"I might say the Government runs all over the turf here with respect to all kinds of allegations, because they said nothing in the pretrial motion; they were mute on why they failed to indict this man within 17 months and what they were doing.","start":1738.888,"stop":1753.102,"duration":14.21}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, why should they say anything?","start":1753.102,"stop":1755.153,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they have some obligation to the -- let me say this, Justice --","start":1755.153,"stop":1758.807,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Under what authority?","start":1758.807,"stop":1759.813,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me say this, Justice --","start":1759.813,"stop":1760.753,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Under what authority did the man --","start":1760.753,"stop":1761.642,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the Marion case.","start":1761.642,"stop":1763.701,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"And precisely what language in Marion do you rely on for them to have any duty to speak?","start":1763.701,"stop":1768.553,"duration":4.85}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"The pre-accusation delay, 17, 18 months, the question that there was the substance of material actual prejudice that this Court has stated would be a Fifth Amendment violation in Marion.","start":1768.553,"stop":1780.036,"duration":11.48},{"text":"I might say, Justice Rehnquist, that in Marion, there was no evidence of the Government delaying deliberately to get a tactical advantage over the defendant; there was governmental negligence.","start":1780.036,"stop":1791.912,"duration":11.88}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But the indictment was not dismissed in Marion, either, was it?","start":1791.912,"stop":1794.286,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it was sent back by this Court to see whether the defendant could prove actual prejudice, that’s all.","start":1794.286,"stop":1801.296,"duration":7.01}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"And wasn’t there also language in Marion that talked about tactical advantage to the Government?","start":1801.296,"stop":1806.288,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"All they said was, we understand that the Government concedes to that.","start":1806.288,"stop":1809.696,"duration":3.41},{"text":"That’s all this Court said.","start":1809.696,"stop":1811.358,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"So, well, unless the defendant comes in on his motion, and presumably he has the burden of proof on a motion like that, and makes a prima facie case that the Marion requirements are there, why is the burden on the Government to go forward and do anything?","start":1811.358,"stop":1825.388,"duration":14.03}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we didn’t say the Government had any burden.","start":1825.388,"stop":1828.098,"duration":2.71},{"text":"We assume the burden of the motion.","start":1828.098,"stop":1830.252,"duration":2.15},{"text":"The Government didn’t do anything.","start":1830.252,"stop":1832.691,"duration":2.44},{"text":"I mean, the Government talks about all the bad things that are going to happen to them in the event this Court decides that the indictment should be dismissed, that this is going to interfere with their investigation of crimes and society and defendant, everybody is going to … the whole administration of justice is going to collapse.","start":1832.691,"stop":1849.238,"duration":16.55},{"text":"All they had to do, Justice Rehnquist, is come in and say, ”We moved our finger from A to “B.","start":1849.238,"stop":1855.938,"duration":6.7},{"text":"They didn’t say that.","start":1855.938,"stop":1857.811,"duration":1.87},{"text":"Well, I am not --","start":1857.811,"stop":1858.568,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but your position under my understanding of Marion is correct if the case you made out on your burden of proof satisfied all the elements of Marion.","start":1858.568,"stop":1871.791,"duration":13.22},{"text":"But if any of those elements were left in dispute, then the Government could stand mute and quite conceivably properly win the motion.","start":1871.791,"stop":1880.478,"duration":8.69}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I am saying that my reading of Marion is certainly different to than the solicitor’s reading of Marion, and maybe I read Marion and it says very definitely, ”If the defendant can go back to trial and can at the trial prove actual prejudice, then he should win his case on a motion to dismiss the indictment”.","start":1880.478,"stop":1900.482,"duration":20}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"And you say the proof that a witness had died without proof as to what that witness would testify is the proof of actual prejudice?","start":1900.482,"stop":1906.601,"duration":6.12}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me say this, Justice Rehnquist, that the Government never appealed the essential finding that Tom Stewart would have testified that Lovasco did not know the guns were stolen at the time that he supplied the guns to Lovasco.","start":1906.601,"stop":1920.453,"duration":13.85},{"text":"Now, that is essential testimony under 18 U.S.C. § 1708, the knowledge of stolen - that I know these guns were stolen, that’s the essential testimony, it’s the bare guts of a defense to that kind of a case, and I might say that that is a finding of the Eight Circuit.","start":1920.453,"stop":1939.909,"duration":19.46},{"text":"The Government has not appealed that material prejudice that the defendant has suffered as a result of this delay to this Court; that’s a finding this Court has to accept.","start":1939.909,"stop":1949.637,"duration":9.73}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"How much delay does there have to be before a defendant is entitled to dismissal on the basis of actual prejudice?","start":1949.637,"stop":1958.029,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"I wouldn’t want to set up any standards on that, Justice.","start":1958.029,"stop":1960.419,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, there can be great prejudice, let’s assume an alleged bank robbery on one day and the key witness for the defense, whose defense, say, is an alibi, let's say, dies the day after the robbery.","start":1960.419,"stop":1977.053,"duration":16.63}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1977.053,"stop":1977.197,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s terrible prejudice, and that’s caused by delay.","start":1977.197,"stop":1979.742,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly.","start":1979.742,"stop":1980.053,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"If I delay, the fact the indictment wasn’t brought on the afternoon of the robbery.","start":1980.053,"stop":1984.593,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that would be an extreme situation.","start":1984.593,"stop":1987.041,"duration":2.45},{"text":"I might say that -- you know, this Court has --","start":1987.041,"stop":1989.717,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"General delays, Congress has set statutes to limitations, which are presumptively the period during which an indictment need be returned; is that correct?","start":1989.717,"stop":1998.071,"duration":8.35}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"But this Court in Marion said that doesn’t set up all the standards with respect to when there is a constitutional right involved and this Court specifically stated that when the Fifth Amendment Due Process question is involved on pre-accusation delay that that’s a matter that can be asserted and the courts will listen to it.","start":1998.071,"stop":2013.569,"duration":15.5}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how much delay?","start":2013.569,"stop":2015.155,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not going to say how much delay, but I believe that this Court could say reasonable delay based upon --","start":2015.155,"stop":2020.441,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, reasonable is presumably a statute of limitations, isn’t it?","start":2020.441,"stop":2022.56,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"But I -- no, I don’t think so, not when there is a question of prejudice to the defendant.","start":2022.56,"stop":2027.03,"duration":4.47},{"text":"I think based -- this Court doesn’t really have to deal with the amount of time, and I might say that in Dickey and --","start":2027.03,"stop":2032.422,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it certainly does.","start":2032.422,"stop":2033.417,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in the Dickey and in Marion and in Barker, the Court didn’t set out any limits that this is particularly the situation.","start":2033.417,"stop":2040.788,"duration":7.37},{"text":"In Barker v. Wingo, Justice Powell didn’t say that “We’re going to say that all these things have to be proven in order to show a Sixth Amendment violation of the Constitution”.","start":2040.788,"stop":2051.906,"duration":11.12},{"text":"It says, “These are the things we should consider, and the trial court should be given certain latitude to make these decisions based upon what he finds, based upon the facts in front of him”.","start":2051.906,"stop":2061.514,"duration":9.61},{"text":"And I feel that in this kind of a situation, where Lovasco kept calling the Government, Justice Marshall, and saying … he didn’t say, “I want to be” -- he essentially said, “I want to be indicted.","start":2061.514,"stop":2073.704,"duration":12.19},{"text":"Do something.","start":2073.704,"stop":2074.15,"duration":0.45},{"text":"Let me know if I am innocent or I am going to be indicted”.","start":2074.15,"stop":2077.021,"duration":2.87},{"text":"He did it.","start":2077.021,"stop":2077.958,"duration":0.94},{"text":"So even though criminals or defendants are not called upon to ask that question, in this case Lovasco kept calling the Inspector and saying, “What are you going to do with me? I gave you a statement, what are you going to do.","start":2077.958,"stop":2088.697,"duration":10.74},{"text":"I am concerned about what’s going to happen to me”.","start":2088.697,"stop":2091.866,"duration":3.17},{"text":"And at no time did the Government come back and do anything about it.","start":2091.866,"stop":2096.058,"duration":4.19},{"text":"In fact --","start":2096.058,"stop":2096.617,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Don’t you think that when he did that more than once or twice, that the prosecutors have said, “There’s something going on around here we have been looking to, because that doesn’t happen every day”?","start":2096.617,"stop":2108.462,"duration":11.84}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think so.","start":2108.462,"stop":2108.929,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And would the prosecutor say, “We’ve got to take another look at this”?","start":2108.929,"stop":2111.749,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think so.","start":2111.749,"stop":2112.579,"duration":0.83},{"text":"They didn’t do anything!","start":2112.579,"stop":2113.388,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that’s what they did.","start":2113.388,"stop":2114.707,"duration":1.32},{"text":"They took another look!","start":2114.707,"stop":2116.918,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"17 months later, they took another look and --","start":2116.918,"stop":2119.538,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"When did he start calling?","start":2119.538,"stop":2121.404,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"He called immediately, right after his statement to the Government, when he came in and gave him the full statement in front of his attorney.","start":2121.404,"stop":2128.06,"duration":6.66},{"text":"And I might say that he kept calling, and he expressed his anxiety.","start":2128.06,"stop":2133.59,"duration":5.53},{"text":"And let me say this.","start":2133.59,"stop":2134.643,"duration":1.05},{"text":"When the Government talks about a stipulation made with the defendant’s attorney, that stipulation was that we had no further evidence in this matter.","start":2134.643,"stop":2144.97,"duration":10.33},{"text":"The only time we secured some additional evidence was after the grand jury had returned their indictment against him.","start":2144.97,"stop":2151.651,"duration":6.68}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That is we the Government now.","start":2151.651,"stop":2152.623,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"We the Government, that’s right.","start":2152.623,"stop":2153.928,"duration":1.3},{"text":"We had nothing else.","start":2153.928,"stop":2155.039,"duration":1.11},{"text":"We hadn’t done anything, and they stated there was no evidence at all to the Court as to what they had done for 17 months.","start":2155.039,"stop":2163.695,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"What’s the statute of limitations on this offense?","start":2163.695,"stop":2165.943,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe it’s a five-year statute of limitations.","start":2165.943,"stop":2167.98,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"So that you're quite a bit short of the five years here.","start":2167.98,"stop":2170.794,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"It is, but let me say that this Court has definitely stated both in Dickey and also in Marion that when a constitutional right becomes in some way triggered by the facts, that that’s something this Court is going to listen to and decide whether or not this person should be protected based upon these intervening constitutional rights.","start":2170.794,"stop":2191.813,"duration":21.02}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"So you have less than a third of the time that Congress has said is the reasonable time in which to bring it.","start":2191.813,"stop":2198.044,"duration":6.23},{"text":"We will resume there at 10:00 in the morning.","start":2198.044,"stop":2200.09,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Louis Gilden","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2200.09,"stop":2207.823,"duration":7.73}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Mar  21 - 22, 1977","petitioner":"United States","respondent":"Eugene Lovasco","docket":"75-1844","citation":"431 US 783 (1977)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/431/783","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 9, 1977"}